rComments: If you want an A, memorize all the vocab, important names, experiments, and take detailed notes in lecture. Type your lecture notes because he can go deep into detail. Consider buying the study guide, it helped me a lot. Some practice questions in there end up on the exam. You can get an A as long as you are willing to work for it. Decent lecturer.

The hardest part of this class was the sheer amount of information stuffed into 4 exams with 55 questions. The readings and the lectures were totally unrelated but both were on the exam. Curve was EXTREMELY generous however.
Very nice and helpful

one of the worst professors i've ever had. he mumbles a lot, repeats the same sentence 10 times at a rate of 0.2 mph, his lectures aren't clear. you have to read the textbook because its on the exam but he doesn't go over anything that's in the book. exams are harder than you'd expect

His is fun and states everything clearly in the lecture. You should write some notes in lecture and also read some book, but materials are not hard. So as long as you attend the lecture and read book, you will get an A.

By Jove, I could not figure out why his teeth are disgusting. They were so distracting even when I sat in the back. Anyway, READ the book AND go to class. Failed the first test because I did neither, and ended up with a B. I redeemed myself with 3 more tests and a generous curve. Do the subject pool, it's required. That's how idiots get C's.

This class should be easy, 4 NONCONSECUTIVE exams and 6 subject pool participations, however if you never have taken a psych class (like me) DO NOT take this class with him. I feel like this class is easier for ppl who have prior knowledge. His examples go on for 20 minutes and lectures seem to take forever. He does curve the grades, which is aplus
Great teacher. The material is interesting and the tests are not hard as long as you attend/pay attention in lecture AND read the assigned chapters.

Read the textbook, go to class and take a lot of notes. With these, you'll do great one the exam. For the first exam, 43/50 = A. Material is interesting though, so its not too hard to concentrate. If that doesn't work for you, bring a recorder.

I liked Srull. I think he does tend to lose track of himself every so often, but that's part of the fun. Read the book, no really, do it, and take notes in class no matter how he rambles, and you'll be good to go. Three exams make up your grade, but they are curved significantly. Social Cognition was really interesting.

He does ramble in the class, some people get bored, but exams are fine if you study both lecture notes and textbooks. My highest exam score: 47/50. Make sure you read textbooks thoroughly. If you miss class then get notes from classmates, since he doesn't post it online. Be aware that his letter grade don't include +/- so it's either A or B.

avoid this class i hated srull. awful professor should not be here. sucks. if you are a freshman don't take this class until your sophomore year or atleast until your g.p.a. is high enough to handle the toll this class will take on it. i cannot tell you to avoid this class enough. BOOOOO!!!

A few ?s... 1. Why is this awful professor rated so high on this website 2. Why is professor at U of I. The avg of each of the tests is a D and then gets curved, why is that positive? Lecture is awful and hard to follow. I would say read the book but that might not help. Take psych at a community college or something, not with this guy!

If you are a good test taker or have previously taken AP Psych definitely take PSYC 100 Section X with Srull! Just show up to class, take notes, manage your time well so you can finish the module readings and you will get an A. The psych studies are interesting and some of them pay you for participating. This is a very straight forward class.

Although attendence is not mandatory, getting an A in this class is highly dependent on your regular attendance. Srull is an entertaining professor and keeps students' attention fairly well. Make sure you read the book, because he will pull about 25-30% of the exam questions from it.

What a dreadful professor. Rambles on with unrelated anecdotes and focuses on topics really unrelated to social cognition. We spent the last few weeks on evolutionary psychology for gods sakes. I'm not sure what we learned in this class that's related to social cognition at all. Pretty easy class though if you can stand to go to class.

The only grades come from exams which are *mostly* lecture based, so go to lectures. He explains things very thoroughly, which can be helpful, but also boring at times. The exams are not too hard, and are curved. My raw score was 78% which ended up being a solid A.

Awesome teacher.Class is interesting/funny and hes reasonable.changed a test two days before we were supposed to have it because someone raised their hand and asked him to bc of the heavy reading load,so he held a class vote right there. Going to class is pretty crucial, not mandatory.Worst part of the class is the book, which you do need to read.

i thought X would be a breeze, and granted it prolly would have been if id tried harder. class was boring to me because it took him 10 minutes to get through one example, so i got frustrated listening to him. but if you pay attention, read the book, you'll do fine.

only 4 difficult test. Half the material comes from the book, half from lecture, and he doesn't talk about whats in the book at all. Very difficult class, stressful, do not take sectin X. He doesn't have office hours. Sometimes hes interesting and funny, but i would rather it not be funny and get a good grade...
